
[1]poem

   PO'EM, n. [L. poema; Gr. to make, to compose songs.]

   1. A metrical composition; a composition in which the verses consist of
   certain measures, whether in blank verse or in rhyme; as the poems of
   Homer or of Milton; opposed to prose.

   2. This term is also applied to some compositions in which the language
   is that of excited imagination; as the poems of Ossian.
